    <body><div type="letter">
      <p>Brighton 9 o'clock. Tuesdy Morg</p>
      <p>I can continue to send you an improved account, tho' I am still far from being, where I was. Every day however brings with it some strong improvement.</p>
      <p>I hope you will forgive my having retained Crawfurd's statement until this morning. I was very anxious to study it thoroughly, from my interest in them; &amp; really I have been unfit till yesterday for the small writing, &amp; somewhat complicated details. It seems altogether rather a curious affair.</p>
      <p>His letter to you is creditable &amp; amiable to the greatest degree. Does it not so strike</p>
      <p>yourself?-- Especially the first page. I conclude there is no chance of revoking the decree of the Master of Rolls.</p>
      <p>I hope you will send me his last letter, &amp; I would return it to you directly.--</p>
      <p>As to the company: I [two words crossed out] suggest the 28th &amp; 29th. [rest of the line strongly crossed out] [most of the line strongly crossed out] Ask the Cottenhams for the 28th . I think these 2 days will be pretty clear of all serious impediments (either for you or me). I should not like to be in for above 2 nights of fatiguing company, remember.</p>
      <p>I hope, dear, that the time &amp;c I am proposing will suit you. My first thought is of your convenience &amp; pleasure, (next to that for the possible as regards myself &amp; my health).</p>
      <p>I think the date I am</p>
      <p>proposing would leave us comfortably free for going to Ashely in tolerable time, if we find we wish to hurry there as early as possible, which perhaps we may.</p>
      <p>I enclose a note, in case you judge proper to send it on to Lady Cottenham, with your to him.</p>
      <p>Will you be so kind as to tell Dr Carpenter (as soon as you can), that I have settled about the tuning of the Piano, as he will find by the result. Tell him also that I shall write to him the first day I can, &amp; only delay because my state does not as yet admit of my writing one word more than is absolutely necessary. Pray give all this message correctly.</p>
      <p>I met the two eldest Miss Cosways (Halliday's nieces)</p>
      <p>last evening at Mrs King's. The eldest is a very superior girl, &amp; interesting. I hear Halliday does not think of returning at present, which I infinitely regret. He has just bought a place near Geneva, &amp; is to part (I think) with the Jura castle. How like him is all this!</p>
      <p>Now Amburgh is arrived here with all his beasts, &amp; a magnificent stud of horses. I go today to see the sights &amp; horsemanship (which latter is I am told first-rate), with Dr King.</p>
      <p>It will be a great pleasure to me, as I never saw Van Amburgh you know; &amp; then too, I love horsemanship so.</p>
      <p>The elephant is to bathe daily in the sea, which seems to excite the public</p>
      <p>expectations prodigiously, &amp; in truth I quite sympathise in this.</p>
      <p>I am delighted to hear of your rides with your son, &amp; with your daughter. I hope she pleases you. She is quite a little fairy, on horseback; &amp; strikingly graceful &amp; clever at it.--</p>
      <p>I wish I could have fixed an earlier time for the party. But I cannot, &amp; I must say what is certain, rather than risk a failure; &amp; worry &amp; annoyance to you.--</p>
      <p>I know you will appreciate, &amp; will believe that I do everything conscientiously, &amp; not to please myself.</p>
      <p>Weddy &amp; Thursday, the 28th &amp; 29th are the 2 days I mention. I repeat it, because I had to blot the passage a</p>
      <p>good deal, owing to a blunder I at first made in the dates.</p>
    </div></body>
